The texts module
================

    >>> import texts
    >>> print texts.__doc__
    Provide methods to handle colour values
    ...

Basic usage:
    >>> hello = texts.colour_text('H', 'green').colour_text('ello ')

Shorter way:
    >>> world = texts.colour('W', 'red').text('orld')

Both methods have same effect
    >>> hello, world
    (<CoulouredTail '\x1b[32mH\x1b[2m\x1b[0m''ello '>, <CoulouredTail '\x1b[31mW\x1b[2m\x1b[0m''orld'>)

Adds in ANSI sequences (looks better on terminal than in a doctest)
    >>> print hello, world
    [32mH[2m[0mello  [31mW[2m[0morld

Convenience method to highlight initials

    >>> foo = texts.colour('H', 'red').colour('ello')
    >>> foo == texts.colour_initial('Hello', 'red')
    True

